
Preamble

We, the peoples of Earth—united in our shared humanity,
affirming the dignity and equality of every person, honoring
cultural diversity, and committed to justice, sustainability,
peace, and environmental stewardship—do hereby enact this
Constitution for global governance, to secure the rights and
responsibilities of all and to govern in common trust for
present and future generations.

Article I – Fundamental Rights and Freedoms

Every human is born free and equal in dignity and rights.

Each person has the right to life, liberty, security,
expression, movement, belief, education, health, and a safe
environment.

No one shall be subjected to torture, slavery, discrimination,
or discrimination based on race, nationality, gender, religion,
language, social or economic status.

Collective rights: indigenous communities and cultural groups
shall have the right to preserve heritage, language, and
traditions.

Environmental rights: a clean, healthy, and ecologically
balanced environment is guaranteed, and future generations have
a right to planetary integrity.

Article II – Principles of Governance

Governance shall follow democratic participation, subsidiarity
(decisions made as close to affected individuals as possible),
transparency, accountability, rule of law, and equality under
the law.

The Earth Compact Constitution is the supreme legal authority;
existing and national laws are subordinate where they conflict
with this Constitution.

All persons, governments, institutions, and corporations are
bound by it.

Article III – Structure of GovernmentSection 1. The Global
Assembly

A body of representatives elected proportionally by global
population, including seats reserved for Indigenous Peoples and
historically marginalized communities. The Assembly enacts
global statutes, approves global budgets, and ratifies
treaties.

Section 2. The Global Council

An executive council composed of representatives from major
regions and continental federations. It enforces Assembly
decisions, coordinates global policy, and manages emergencies
and global projects.

Section 3. The World Court

An independent judiciary vested with power to adjudicate
violations of this Constitution, inter-state disputes, and
crimes against humanity and ecocide.

Section 4. Specialized Agencies

Autonomous agencies under constitutional mandate—covering public
health, environmental protection, science and innovation, social
development, digital governance, and disaster response (akin to
a Global Health Constitution proposed overlaying WHO) (Reddit,
Reddit).

Article IV – Global Economic & Resource Governance

A global taxation system funds Planetary Resource Dividend—basic
universal social services and income funded via global resource
fees (carbon, data, commons usage).

Wealth redistribution mechanisms ensure equity and reduce
extreme inequality.

Natural resources of global significance (atmosphere, deep
seabed, biodiversity hotspots) are treated as shared commons
and conserved for current and future generations.

Article V – Environmental Duty and Climate Action

All nations commit to net-zero greenhouse gas emissions by
specified targets, conservation of biodiversity, and
sustainable resource use.

Ecocide and large-scale environmental harm are globally
prosecutable offenses.

Global reserve zones are established to protect endangered
ecosystems, with enforcement by international environmental
agents.

Article VI – Peace, Security & Conflict Resolution

Nations renounce war where possible; disputes are resolved
through arbitration, mediation, and the World Court.

A global peacekeeping service responds to genocide, war crimes,
and crimes against humanity.

Phased disarmament of weapons of mass destruction is mandatory.

Article VII – Science, Technology & Innovation

Scientific research is coordinated globally to address
challenges like pandemics, climate crises, and energy
transitions.

Knowledge and innovation are open-access, with equitable
benefit-sharing globally.

Ethical oversight councils review emerging technologies (e.g.
AI, biotech).

Article VIII – Education, Culture & Communication

Universal, inclusive, multilingual education is guaranteed.

Cultural diversity is celebrated—heritage preserved while
promoting intercultural exchange.

Digital rights, including privacy, freedom of information, and
internet access, are protected.

Article IX – Participatory Democracy & Amendment Process

Amendments may originate from the Global Assembly or via
petitions signed by ≥10% of the global population.

Ratification requires a two-thirds Assembly vote and approval by
a global referendum with at least 60% turnout in favor.

The Constitution is designed as a living, open-source document
subject to continuous global deliberation and crowd-sourced
reform (Reddit, Reddit).

Article X – Transitional Arrangements & Implementation

A Transitional Council (composed of international experts, civil
society, and elected delegates) supervises phased establishment
of institutional bodies.

Initial phases include reform of existing international bodies
(e.g. democratizing UN, forming continental federations,
launching citizen assemblies) leading toward full
constitutional governance.

Safeguards: decentralized power, transparency, citizen juries,
and audit systems prevent concentration of authority.

📌 Notes & Foundations

This mirrors earlier constitutional attempts like the
Constitution for the Federation of Earth (1968–1991) and
structures emerging from proposals by global civil society
(Wikipedia).

It also builds conceptually from the UN Charter, which though
treaty‑based shares constitutional functions such as universal
scope, fundamental purposes, membership equality, and supremacy
over certain domains (Reddit).

Embraces modern constitutional models of open‑source drafting
and participatory amendment processes (Reddit).

This constitution‑style text provides a structured legal
foundation for global governance built on universal rights,
democratic structure, environmental duty, equity, and
participatory evolution. Let me know if you’d like
additions—such as more detail on an ethics council,
transitional voting mechanisms, or enforcement clauses.

